00:00:10.104 --> 00:00:11.229
KRIST NOVOCELIC: Thank you.

00:00:14.410 --> 00:00:16.900
How did I get involved in
election reform coming out

00:00:16.900 --> 00:00:18.890
of the music industry
and music scene?

00:00:18.890 --> 00:00:20.770
And it was through music.

00:00:20.770 --> 00:00:25.290
I got politically involved
in Washington state.

00:00:25.290 --> 00:00:30.850
Bands like Pearl Jam, Nirvana,
Alice in Chains, Soundgarden

00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:36.370
were just taking the world
by storm in 1992, 1991.

00:00:36.370 --> 00:00:39.640
And at the same time, the
Washington state legislature

00:00:39.640 --> 00:00:42.130
had this censorship bill.

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:43.550
It was really bad.

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:47.540
And the city of Seattle had
this teen dance ordinance.

00:00:47.540 --> 00:00:53.140
So if you were an adult
between the ages of 18 and 20,

00:00:53.140 --> 00:00:57.160
you couldn't go see Mudhoney
play the Central Tavern because

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:57.740
of the rules.

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:02.180
And so Seattle music was being
celebrated internationally.

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:06.140
But here in our own backyard,
we were getting repressed.

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:11.730
And so I got involved with other
people in the music community.

00:01:11.730 --> 00:01:14.690
And we were proactive about,
hey, this is a good thing,

00:01:14.690 --> 00:01:17.510
and you should really
foster and encourage it.

00:01:17.510 --> 00:01:20.520
And we started to turn
things around where

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:23.730
music's now celebrated in
Seattle and Washington state.

00:01:23.730 --> 00:01:25.850
But it wasn't easy.

00:01:25.850 --> 00:01:29.270
One of the things,
personally, was, that's

00:01:29.270 --> 00:01:31.546
how I got my civic education.

00:01:31.546 --> 00:01:32.670
Like, how does a bill work?

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:33.794
You know "I'm Just a Bill."

00:01:33.794 --> 00:01:36.290
Remember the little
cartoon or whatever, which

00:01:36.290 --> 00:01:39.470
has a cool bass line on it.

00:01:39.470 --> 00:01:44.510
And not just civics,
but the whole process--

00:01:44.510 --> 00:01:47.660
like, all right, the
bill, and you're a law.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:51.500
But there's all these interests
that work legislation--

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:56.650
the music community,
beer distributors, fans,

00:01:56.650 --> 00:02:00.710
record stores, and
people coming together

00:02:00.710 --> 00:02:02.600
and just engaging the system.

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:04.020
And there was a
lot of enthusiasm.

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:05.735
Like, hey, we're going
to have a concert.

00:02:05.735 --> 00:02:06.860
Are you going to come down?

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:07.550
Absolutely.

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:09.229
I want to be part
of the concert,

00:02:09.229 --> 00:02:12.980
because it's an event
for our political goals--

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:14.001
like a benefit concert.

00:02:14.001 --> 00:02:16.250
And then, are you going to
come to the public hearing?

00:02:16.250 --> 00:02:16.610
Yeah.

00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:17.610
We're going to be there.

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:19.297
We're going to testify
for better laws.

00:02:19.297 --> 00:02:20.630
And then, are you going to vote?

00:02:20.630 --> 00:02:21.740
It's like, no, not really.

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:22.510
Like, why not?

00:02:22.510 --> 00:02:24.093
And it's just like,
well, I just don't

00:02:24.093 --> 00:02:26.150
feel like my vote matters.

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:27.880
And part of that
education was really,

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:30.440
like, it kind of doesn't
really matter, does it?

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:33.110
Because we have this
representative here in Seattle.

00:02:33.110 --> 00:02:35.530
She's great.

00:02:35.530 --> 00:02:38.634
But if there's, like,
100% turnout for her,

00:02:38.634 --> 00:02:39.550
does it really matter?

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:42.140
Because she's going
to win anyway.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:45.612
And then this other person who's
against us, he's really bad,

00:02:45.612 --> 00:02:46.570
and he's out to get us.

00:02:46.570 --> 00:02:50.230
But he's in a safe seat, Krist.

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:52.355
I don't think you can really
do anything about him.

00:02:52.355 --> 00:02:53.104
It's like, really?

00:02:53.104 --> 00:02:54.244
What do you mean safe seat?

00:02:54.244 --> 00:02:56.160
Well, this is how it
works, and this and that.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:58.285
Jesus, there's got to be
a better system than that.

00:02:58.285 --> 00:03:00.070
It's, yeah, well, you know.

00:03:00.070 --> 00:03:00.790
So at the time--

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:03.730
this was about 1995--

00:03:03.730 --> 00:03:04.790
I'm on the internet.

00:03:04.790 --> 00:03:08.110
I think I had 110 version--

00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:10.010
two 56Ks they put together--

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:12.020
ISDN line or something
like that it was called.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:13.040
Do you remember that?

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:16.690
Anyway, so I was faster than
all my neighbors and anything.

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:21.210
And I was on a search
engine called AltaVista.

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:22.820
And then I'd plug in keywords--

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:25.400
election reform, voting
reform, elections,

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:27.294
voting in the United States.

00:03:27.294 --> 00:03:28.710
And this one group
would come up--

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:30.800
FairVote, FairVote,
FairVote, the Center

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:32.390
for Voting and Democracy.

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:34.730
I'm like, well,
that's interesting.

00:03:34.730 --> 00:03:36.430
And who's their chairman?

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:38.415
John B. Anderson.

00:03:38.415 --> 00:03:39.230
Oh, I remember him.

00:03:39.230 --> 00:03:42.950
He ran for president in
1980 as an independent.

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:44.520
And he had this iconic campaign.

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:46.190
He was running neck and
neck with the Democrat

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:48.360
and Republicans that summer
in 1980 in the campaign.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.200
It was really disruptive.

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:57.090
He went-- what's the
word I'm looking for--

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:57.590
viral.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:58.550
He went viral.

00:03:58.550 --> 00:03:59.930
He caught all this imagination.

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:00.540
ROB RITCHIE: "Doonesbury."

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:01.415
KRIST NOVOCELIC: What's that?

00:04:01.415 --> 00:04:02.060
ROB RITCHIE:
"Doonesbury" liked him.

00:04:02.060 --> 00:04:03.770
KRIST NOVOCELIC:
"Doonesbury" liked him.

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:06.060
So it's just like,
well, he's independent.

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:08.000
Well, I come from the
independent music scene.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.200
So then FairVote has these,
what is ranked choice voting?

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:13.900
You know, in instant
runoff voting,

00:04:13.900 --> 00:04:15.590
you rank these candidates--

00:04:15.590 --> 00:04:18.230
proportional representation
for the United States.

00:04:18.230 --> 00:04:19.445
We can do that in America?

00:04:22.550 --> 00:04:24.380
They call it the
alternative vote,

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:25.464
this ranked choice voting.

00:04:25.464 --> 00:04:27.963
I'm like, oh, well, alternative
music is what I come out of.

00:04:27.963 --> 00:04:29.700
So it was all kind
of interesting.

00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:34.910
And so I looked into it
and I became fascinated.

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:39.380
Because it just seemed
so cutting edge and so

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:41.100
transformative.

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:46.100
And with Nirvana and the music
scene that we came out of,

00:04:46.100 --> 00:04:50.890
it seemed like most rock music
was really lame in the 1980s--

00:04:50.890 --> 00:04:56.660
this kind of predictable
'70s rehash into the '80s.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:04:59.390
And so we came out of this
music scene that kind of

00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:01.656
revolutionized the whole thing.

00:05:01.656 --> 00:05:03.530
And so there was this
whole new wave of music

00:05:03.530 --> 00:05:06.420
that came in-- grunge rock,
alternative, or whatever.

00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:08.637
And so it seemed like
the same sensibility.

00:05:08.637 --> 00:05:10.970
Well, how do we do with our
elections and voting-- like,

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:15.530
maybe we can have this new kind
of wave of democracy take over?

00:05:15.530 --> 00:05:18.350
And again, doing
those word searches--

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:21.290
it was just like, well, we have
proportional representation

00:05:21.290 --> 00:05:23.161
in the United States?

00:05:23.161 --> 00:05:23.660
Wow.

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:26.830
Isn't that like how
they vote in Europe?

00:05:26.830 --> 00:05:28.600
And it's like, no.

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:30.806
It's kind of like it.

00:05:30.806 --> 00:05:32.180
Because it's not
winner-take-all.

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:35.350
It's not where you have one
district where everybody votes

00:05:35.350 --> 00:05:37.900
and whoever gets the
most votes represents

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:40.210
100% of the district.

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:42.260
With proportional
representation,

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:44.950
you have multi winners.

00:05:44.950 --> 00:05:47.240
And it's not a
winner-take-all system.

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:50.320
So you can have, say, a
district with three people

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:51.650
who represent everybody.

00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:54.580
So it's like a slice of a pie.

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:56.950
Everybody gets their share
of the vote-- like one third,

00:05:56.950 --> 00:05:58.840
one third, one third.

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:01.150
But in Europe-- wow.

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:03.010
In Europe, they
vote for parties.

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:06.530
They don't even vote for people.

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:07.830
Is that really a good idea?

00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:09.390
Maybe.

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:10.350
I don't know.

00:06:10.350 --> 00:06:13.110
In Europe, it
takes, like, 2%, 3%,

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:15.130
4% of the vote to get elected.

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:17.130
I don't know if that
would be very popular here

00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:18.090
in the United States.

00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:20.370
So looking into the
FairVote website,

00:06:20.370 --> 00:06:24.180
reading scholarly
papers, and it's

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:28.380
like, there's American versions
of proportional representation.

00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:30.990
So they're candidate-based.

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:33.180
So you vote for the person.

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:35.490
You don't vote for a party.

00:06:35.490 --> 00:06:38.105
The thresholds to get
elected are a lot higher.

00:06:38.105 --> 00:06:41.700
And there's versions that are
used to this day in the United

00:06:41.700 --> 00:06:42.630
States.

00:06:42.630 --> 00:06:45.090
100 municipalities
in the United States

00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:49.200
use some version of
proportional representation.

00:06:49.200 --> 00:06:54.690
And it could take 33% of
the vote to get elected,

00:06:54.690 --> 00:07:00.150
or 25%, or 20%, or 15%.

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:02.934
But it's a lot higher
than, say, in Israel.

00:07:02.934 --> 00:07:04.350
They just raised
it up to-- what--

00:07:04.350 --> 00:07:07.650
3 and 1/2%, 4%,
something like that.

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:10.290
So there's these
American versions

00:07:10.290 --> 00:07:12.690
of proportional representation.

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:16.230
And I thought that would
be very transformative.

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:22.050
Like, wow, you feel like
your vote would matter.

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:27.420
You could be you could be,
like, a Democrat in a rural area

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:30.360
and you could actually vote
for and elect somebody.

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:35.580
I'm an Independent, by the way.

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:39.030
But where I live, Democrats,
they pull in about 43%

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:42.240
of the vote on the coast
of Washington state.

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:45.330
And they elect nobody.

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:48.420
And then the Republican, she
wins every couple of years

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:49.140
automatically.

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:53.070
And then the Democrats
don't put any money--

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:55.391
the Democratic leader
here in San Francisco,

00:07:55.391 --> 00:07:57.390
she doesn't put any of
those millions of dollars

00:07:57.390 --> 00:08:01.074
that they collect selling
access to the Congress--

00:08:01.074 --> 00:08:03.240
they don't put any money--
they just wrote that off.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:06.840
Those Democrats
are orphan voters.

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:13.497
But then on the other hand,
you have Democrats in Seattle.

00:08:13.497 --> 00:08:14.580
And it was the same thing.

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:16.030
It's just like,
if you have 100%--

00:08:16.030 --> 00:08:19.500
they have, like, 70%
turnout for Democrats there.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:21.820
And there's all
these surplus votes.

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:23.280
And it doesn't really add up.

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:25.720
And then there's
Republicans in Seattle.

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:27.840
They get nothing.

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:30.540
But we're all taxpayers.

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:34.020
We're all subject to the
rules and laws of the land.

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:36.960
And so somehow, there's
this current system--

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:40.409
this winner-take-all system
with single-member districts.

00:08:40.409 --> 00:08:42.870
It decides who the
winners and losers are.

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:49.070
We have an
independent commission

00:08:49.070 --> 00:08:51.227
to draw districts
in Washington state.

00:08:51.227 --> 00:08:53.810
And it's just like they decide
who the winners and losers are.

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:55.476
It's not even an
independent commission.

00:08:55.476 --> 00:08:57.890
It's a bipartisan commission,
where they the Democrats

00:08:57.890 --> 00:08:59.832
and Republicans
collude, and they say,

00:08:59.832 --> 00:09:01.790
you're going to be the
winner, and you're going

00:09:01.790 --> 00:09:03.560
to be the loser to the voters.

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:07.130
In California, you
have a commission now.

00:09:07.130 --> 00:09:09.680
The first time you
used it was in 2011.

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:12.260
And that was way better--

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:16.720
way better-- than
what you had before.

00:09:16.720 --> 00:09:20.225
But then wasn't a DOS
system better than--

00:09:20.225 --> 00:09:21.170
I don't know.

00:09:21.170 --> 00:09:23.440
What was before
that-- punch cards?

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:25.010
You know what I mean?

00:09:25.010 --> 00:09:26.100
You following me?

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:27.270
So there's this commission--

00:09:27.270 --> 00:09:29.340
like, you've got an
independent commission.

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.740
We took it out of the
hands of politicians,

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:36.830
and we gave the
choice for voters to--

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:40.070
the commission decides
who wins and who loses.

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:45.650
So proportional representation
is, we decide who votes.

00:09:45.650 --> 00:09:48.710
So that's how I got--

00:09:48.710 --> 00:09:53.110
I just felt it's just
a way better system.

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:56.690
And so people aren't
really like plugged into--

00:09:56.690 --> 00:09:59.240
I guess it's really
new to a lot of people.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:03.560
But I got involved
with FairVote.

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:06.780
And so we work a lot with
the Voting Rights Act.

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:09.470
And here in Santa
Clara, there's going

00:10:09.470 --> 00:10:10.970
to be an initiative
on the ballot

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:13.010
to change to proportional
representation

00:10:13.010 --> 00:10:15.830
as a remedy to the
Voting Rights Act.

00:10:15.830 --> 00:10:20.120
And a lot of people will
assume that the Voting Rights

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:23.750
Act doesn't say anything about
having these this district

00:10:23.750 --> 00:10:25.130
elections as being the remedy.

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:27.740
And actually, that's
where you find

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:30.980
proportional representation
in the case law in the United

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:32.210
States.

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.880
It's coming out of
the Voting Rights Act.

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:38.370
Because it gives
minorities a voice.

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:41.720
So it facilitates
minority representation.

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:43.830
It's just that simple.

00:10:43.830 --> 00:10:46.550
So if you're a
political minority--

00:10:46.550 --> 00:10:50.120
say, a Republican in
this Democratic town--

00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:54.000
you could possibly elect
somebody on your council.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:55.160
You're a racial minority.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:58.040
Absolutely you can
elect somebody,

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:03.860
if the people of that race
are like-minded enough

00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:08.510
to elect somebody.

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:09.680
But it doesn't assume that.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:15.080
When you put districts together
with the district elections,

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:17.180
that assumes that people
are going to be like,

00:11:17.180 --> 00:11:19.430
well, you're Latino and
you're going to vote Democrat,

00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:20.805
or you're black,
and you're going

00:11:20.805 --> 00:11:23.870
to vote Democrat, which is fine.

00:11:23.870 --> 00:11:27.140
But the proportional
representation

00:11:27.140 --> 00:11:29.600
doesn't necessarily
make that assumption.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:32.430
It lets the voters decide.

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:35.210
And so that's basically
my stake in this,

00:11:35.210 --> 00:11:38.150
and why I'm such a
forceful advocate for it.

00:11:38.150 --> 00:11:40.550
Because we're taxpayers.

00:11:40.550 --> 00:11:44.180
We're subject to the rules
and the laws of the land.

00:11:44.180 --> 00:11:48.440
And we should
decide who we elect.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.200
Instead, we have
political insiders--

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:57.590
the same people who sell
access to Sacramento or Olympia

00:11:57.590 --> 00:12:00.500
or Salem or whatever
the statehouse,

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:01.625
or the US Congress--

00:12:06.030 --> 00:12:09.920
today's boss-- those are the
people who are also making

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:13.160
decisions on the
most fundamental part

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:14.090
of our democracy--

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:19.010
the interface between the
citizen and government.

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.830
And they're saying,
here is this system.

00:12:21.830 --> 00:12:25.580
It's the winner-take-all,
single-member system.

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:27.330
And this is how it works.

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:30.740
We draw these districts,
and then you vote.

00:12:30.740 --> 00:12:33.715
And then we make sure that this
district is safe for Democrats.

00:12:33.715 --> 00:12:35.090
We make sure that
this district's

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:36.550
safe for Republicans.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:39.610
And maybe there's a few
toss-up districts in between.

00:12:39.610 --> 00:12:43.130
And I think we can do a lot
better than that, especially

00:12:43.130 --> 00:12:44.210
in the 21st century.

00:12:44.210 --> 00:12:47.210
Everybody's really concerned
about gerrymandering.

00:12:47.210 --> 00:12:49.340
And if you want a solution
for gerrymandering,

00:12:49.340 --> 00:12:57.550
absolutely, let's have
independent commissions.

00:12:57.550 --> 00:13:00.400
But that's just
part of the deal.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:03.220
Voters need to have
a say, ultimately,

00:13:03.220 --> 00:13:05.950
on who represents us.

00:13:05.950 --> 00:13:08.500
And that's what proportional
representation is.

00:13:08.500 --> 00:13:11.810
There are American
versions of it.

00:13:11.810 --> 00:13:13.570
They're constitutionally
protected.

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:16.000
They've been scrutinized
by the courts.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.570
And they're in use
in the United States.

00:13:19.570 --> 00:13:21.470
It's that simple.

00:13:21.470 --> 00:13:22.760
How am I on time here?

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:23.290
12:20.

00:13:23.290 --> 00:13:26.214
So I guess we can move on.

00:13:26.214 --> 00:13:26.880
