rank more than one
candidate when they do

00:45:35.702 --> 00:45:37.410
ranked choice voting,
or do a lot of them

00:45:37.410 --> 00:45:39.090
just still put one person in?

00:45:39.090 --> 00:45:41.200
And if they aren't putting
in a second person,

00:45:41.200 --> 00:45:42.646
is it because of
lack of education

00:45:42.646 --> 00:45:43.770
about the other candidates?

00:45:43.770 --> 00:45:45.228
Is there a way to
encourage people?

00:45:45.228 --> 00:45:47.519
Because that would be the
biggest thing I would think

00:45:47.519 --> 00:45:48.060
would happen.

00:45:48.060 --> 00:45:49.410
People would be like, I don't
know who these people are,

00:45:49.410 --> 00:45:50.580
and they just
wouldn't even bother.

00:45:50.580 --> 00:45:51.371
ROB RITCHIE: Right.

00:45:51.371 --> 00:45:53.910
Well, it's an
interesting question.

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:55.830
So the more interested
they are in the race,

00:45:55.830 --> 00:45:57.570
the more they'll rank everybody.

00:45:57.570 --> 00:45:59.221
So just as an
example, we did a poll

00:45:59.221 --> 00:46:00.720
in the Republican
presidential field

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:04.530
at the time of the Iowa caucuses
of real, likely Republican

00:46:04.530 --> 00:46:05.030
voters.

00:46:05.030 --> 00:46:06.900
It was an online
poll with YouGov--

00:46:06.900 --> 00:46:08.700
so a pretty nice
sort of way to be

00:46:08.700 --> 00:46:10.590
able to show your preferences.

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:13.590
Did not say rank everybody, but
it offered them the chance to.

00:46:13.590 --> 00:46:15.167
And more than 90%
ranked them all.

00:46:15.167 --> 00:46:17.750
KRIST NOVOCELIC: How many people
ranked in Santa Fe last week?

00:46:17.750 --> 00:46:19.050
ROB RITCHIE: And
Santa Fe-- exactly.

00:46:19.050 --> 00:46:20.758
We don't actually have
the full data yet.

00:46:20.758 --> 00:46:24.180
But Santa Fe, first
time use of it--

00:46:24.180 --> 00:46:26.550
one is, they're getting
better ballot designs.

00:46:26.550 --> 00:46:28.920
Do some of you vote in
San Francisco or Oakland?

00:46:28.920 --> 00:46:31.710
So they have ranked
choice voting.

00:46:31.710 --> 00:46:34.590
In the mayor's race,
a majority of people

00:46:34.590 --> 00:46:36.780
use all the rankings
allowed, which is three.

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:40.022
A majority of people
will do that for mayor.

00:46:40.022 --> 00:46:41.730
They're not allowed
to do more than three

00:46:41.730 --> 00:46:44.880
in the current ballot design.

00:46:44.880 --> 00:46:47.700
And then if it's like a lower
level board of supervisors

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:50.490
race, a majority will
definitely rank more than one,

00:46:50.490 --> 00:46:52.740
but not as many.

00:46:52.740 --> 00:46:55.849
And so the less you know
about the candidates,

00:46:55.849 --> 00:46:56.890
the more you won't do it.

00:46:56.890 --> 00:46:59.310
But in the Santa Fe
race-- so five candidates.

00:46:59.310 --> 00:47:01.230
It went all the way
through down to two.

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:03.690
When they got to the final
round, of all the people

00:47:03.690 --> 00:47:05.850
that voted in the
first round, 96%

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:07.920
had made a preference
between the final two.

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:09.430
It was kind of cool.

00:47:09.430 --> 00:47:12.090
And you know, it's a
pretty diverse city

00:47:12.090 --> 00:47:13.629
with a lot of differences.

00:47:13.629 --> 00:47:15.420
But people had learned
about the candidates

00:47:15.420 --> 00:47:18.390
and wanted to
indicate a preference.

00:47:18.390 --> 00:47:21.357
The other part of it is that,
now, you have candidates who--

00:47:21.357 --> 00:47:23.940
you're saying like, oh, I don't
know who these candidates are.

00:47:23.940 --> 00:47:26.790
The candidates know
you might think that.

00:47:26.790 --> 00:47:29.250
They have a reason
to engage with you.

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:31.392
So what you're
starting to see is,

00:47:31.392 --> 00:47:33.600
people are starting to get
the playbook of how to win

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:34.260
with ranked choice voting.

00:47:34.260 --> 00:47:36.455
And the playbook is, talk
to more people, which

00:47:36.455 --> 00:47:37.830
is actually kind
of a good thing,

00:47:37.830 --> 00:47:39.190
particularly at the local level.

00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:41.640
So Minneapolis and St. Paul
or places like that are using

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:42.514
ranked choice voting.

00:47:42.514 --> 00:47:46.405
And you're just seeing deeper
levels of conversations going.

00:47:46.405 --> 00:47:48.030
SPEAKER: What are
the biggest obstacles

00:47:48.030 --> 00:47:50.238
to getting ranked choice
voting to be more prevalent?

00:47:50.238 --> 00:47:52.590
Do you see a lot of
opposition from the main two

00:47:52.590 --> 00:47:54.969
political parties?

00:47:54.969 --> 00:47:56.010
KRIST NOVOCELIC: You can.

00:48:00.220 --> 00:48:03.770
There's opposition,
because you bring change.

00:48:03.770 --> 00:48:06.890
And there's a survival
instinct of, say,

00:48:06.890 --> 00:48:08.600
a politician or a
lawmaker to say, well,

00:48:08.600 --> 00:48:11.100
how's this going to
affect my election?

00:48:11.100 --> 00:48:16.214
And you saw it in, say, the
presidential debates in 2016.

00:48:16.214 --> 00:48:17.630
It's just like,
why didn't we have

00:48:17.630 --> 00:48:19.970
more people up there
instead of the Republican

00:48:19.970 --> 00:48:20.720
and the Democrat?

00:48:20.720 --> 00:48:23.780
Because they didn't want
to have any competition.

00:48:23.780 --> 00:48:26.540
And so things are
so polarized now.

00:48:26.540 --> 00:48:30.380
It's like people are just
afraid of the other side.

00:48:30.380 --> 00:48:31.400
And they're so afraid.

00:48:31.400 --> 00:48:33.500
Or they demonize the other side.

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:34.970
And they're so afraid.

00:48:34.970 --> 00:48:37.410
They don't have the
mental bandwidth,

00:48:37.410 --> 00:48:39.500
the cognitive ability
to just say, well,

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:43.892
maybe I should go for this
independent or another voice.

00:48:43.892 --> 00:48:45.350
Because they're
afraid that they're

00:48:45.350 --> 00:48:47.120
going to help the other side.

00:48:47.120 --> 00:48:50.760
And so the wagons are
circled on both sides.

00:48:50.760 --> 00:48:54.570
And so with ranked choice
voting, it's very powerful.

00:48:54.570 --> 00:48:57.030
It's just like, you
have your first choice.

00:48:57.030 --> 00:48:58.940
It's your strongest choice.

00:48:58.940 --> 00:49:00.970
I really, really like her.

00:49:00.970 --> 00:49:02.720
And I'm going to make
her my first choice.

00:49:02.720 --> 00:49:07.940
But you know, she's all right.

00:49:07.940 --> 00:49:10.860
I'm comfortable with making
her my second choice.

00:49:10.860 --> 00:49:14.270
But that second choice is not
hurting your first choice.

00:49:14.270 --> 00:49:18.920
It's a sophisticated way
of ranking your candidates.

00:49:18.920 --> 00:49:24.950
And people are so
polarized now in the tribal

00:49:24.950 --> 00:49:27.101
with the Republicans
and the Democrats.

00:49:27.101 --> 00:49:28.850
And it just seems like
whatever the issues

00:49:28.850 --> 00:49:30.740
are running in the news--

00:49:30.740 --> 00:49:33.890
and then why don't you just
look at your own election

00:49:33.890 --> 00:49:35.090
system in California?

00:49:35.090 --> 00:49:37.340
They just changed the rules.

00:49:37.340 --> 00:49:40.970
You're going to have your
primary election in March.

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:44.930
So all the candidates run
for whatever state office

00:49:44.930 --> 00:49:50.120
in March, or Congress,
or for US Senate.

00:49:50.120 --> 00:49:52.310
And then the top two
candidates, no matter

00:49:52.310 --> 00:49:54.970
if someone has a
majority or not,

00:49:54.970 --> 00:49:58.500
they run again in November.

00:49:58.500 --> 00:50:01.340
That's, like, almost a
whole year of just getting

00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:03.680
stuck with two candidates

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:05.850
I mean, why did the
legislature do that?

00:50:08.370 --> 00:50:10.360
That's a big deal.

00:50:10.360 --> 00:50:13.815
In France, they have
runoff elections.

00:50:13.815 --> 00:50:16.400
In France, they have an
election for their assembly.

00:50:16.400 --> 00:50:19.700
If someone wins a majority in
that district, they're elected.

00:50:19.700 --> 00:50:23.400
If there's no majority, they
have a runoff two weeks later--

00:50:23.400 --> 00:50:24.930
two weeks.

00:50:24.930 --> 00:50:27.260
And here, it's just months.

00:50:27.260 --> 00:50:31.580
And then behind the scenes,
you have all these insiders.

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:33.320
I'm answering this question--

00:50:33.320 --> 00:50:34.190
who's against it?

00:50:34.190 --> 00:50:39.320
Not just the political parties,
which are soft money conduits.

00:50:39.320 --> 00:50:42.980
They sell access to the
legislature to Congress.

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:44.900
Then they raise
millions of dollars.

00:50:44.900 --> 00:50:49.130
And then these bosses dole it
out to who could win or lose.

00:50:49.130 --> 00:50:51.780
There's also these other groups
that work behind the scenes,

00:50:51.780 --> 00:50:54.390
and voters have no
idea who they are.

00:50:54.390 --> 00:50:59.180
And they're chamber of commerce
or unions or identity politics

00:50:59.180 --> 00:51:02.420
groups or some issue groups
on the left and right.

00:51:02.420 --> 00:51:04.340
And they're doing
independent expenditures.

00:51:04.340 --> 00:51:06.470
They're spending
millions of dollars.

00:51:06.470 --> 00:51:10.880
And they don't want
to change that power

00:51:10.880 --> 00:51:12.704
to give voters power.

00:51:12.704 --> 00:51:14.120
Why would they
want to give voters

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:16.200
power when they have the power?

00:51:16.200 --> 00:51:19.984
When you're stuck with two
choices from March to November,

00:51:19.984 --> 00:51:20.900
that's what they want.

00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:23.191
Because if you had more
choices, you'd have more power.

00:51:23.191 --> 00:51:26.430
If you have more power,
then they have less power.

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:28.720
So that's why
they're threatened.

00:51:28.720 --> 00:51:29.930
A lot of them are threatened.

00:51:29.930 --> 00:51:33.110
There's rational, good
government folks in Sacramento

00:51:33.110 --> 00:51:36.320
and on the local level
and in the Congress

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:38.090
that recognize
the value of this.

00:51:38.090 --> 00:51:40.820
But there's also a lot of
people who don't want it,

00:51:40.820 --> 00:51:42.779
because they don't want
to give up their power.

00:51:42.779 --> 00:51:43.528
ROB RITCHIE: Yeah.

00:51:43.528 --> 00:51:45.364
And I'll say, just to
add as a tag to that,

00:51:45.364 --> 00:51:47.155
there's sort of an
insider versus outsider.

00:51:47.155 --> 00:51:48.530
It's not left versus right.

00:51:48.530 --> 00:51:51.350
But it's often like a
younger versus older.

00:51:51.350 --> 00:51:52.850
Some of our most
passionate people--

00:51:52.850 --> 00:51:54.620
the guy we were
working with in Utah--

00:51:54.620 --> 00:51:55.790
conservative Republican.

00:51:55.790 --> 00:51:56.990
He's, like, 29.

00:51:56.990 --> 00:51:58.520
And he's just, like,
really into it.

00:51:58.520 --> 00:52:01.580
And the guy in Georgia who's
really into it is, like, 26.

00:52:01.580 --> 00:52:04.520
And they don't to be that
young to be really leading

00:52:04.520 --> 00:52:05.160
that effort.

00:52:05.160 --> 00:52:07.550
But they tend to be
to be more ready.

00:52:07.550 --> 00:52:11.180
In 2008, when McCain and
Obama ran against each other,

00:52:11.180 --> 00:52:14.201
they had both been prime
sponsors or prime advocates

00:52:14.201 --> 00:52:15.200
of ranked choice voting.

00:52:15.200 --> 00:52:17.540
They were sort of
a little bit of--

00:52:17.540 --> 00:52:20.240
not outsiders, but
kind of change agents.

00:52:20.240 --> 00:52:22.940
And so you will see people like
that who are more like that.

00:52:22.940 --> 00:52:25.940
And you know, the
current DNC chair likes

00:52:25.940 --> 00:52:27.500
ranked choice voting.

00:52:27.500 --> 00:52:30.170
A guy from the second
Republican race

00:52:30.170 --> 00:52:32.030
a few years ago is one
of our key advocates.

00:52:32.030 --> 00:52:35.940
So there are interesting
changes happening.

00:52:35.940 --> 00:52:37.870
And there is resistance.

00:52:37.870 --> 00:52:40.009
But I think a lot of those
folks recognize it's not

00:52:40.009 --> 00:52:41.050
working that well either.

00:52:41.050 --> 00:52:42.960
And they can see that this
is a way to let it breathe.

00:52:42.960 --> 00:52:44.340
I'll just say about
top two and the point

00:52:44.340 --> 00:52:45.420
that Krist is making--

00:52:45.420 --> 00:52:48.402
so you all live in the
top two environment,

00:52:48.402 --> 00:52:50.110
which has some
interesting aspects to it.

00:52:50.110 --> 00:52:51.859
So I don't want to be
just critical of it.

00:52:51.859 --> 00:52:53.910
But a part of it
that's challenging

00:52:53.910 --> 00:52:55.620
is, you only get
to vote for one.

00:52:55.620 --> 00:52:57.540
And so in those primaries,
the first round,

00:52:57.540 --> 00:52:58.980
you only get about for one.

00:52:58.980 --> 00:53:02.250
So Republicans are worried they
might not get someone advancing

00:53:02.250 --> 00:53:04.070
to the general election.

00:53:04.070 --> 00:53:06.570
And that's because there's more
than one Republican running.

00:53:06.570 --> 00:53:08.280
If only one Republican
ran for governor,

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:11.310
they're pretty much a done
deal that they get in.

00:53:11.310 --> 00:53:13.079
But it's a split vote.

00:53:13.079 --> 00:53:15.120
And Democrats are worried
they might not actually

00:53:15.120 --> 00:53:16.669
get any in races
that they otherwise

00:53:16.669 --> 00:53:18.210
could win in the
congressional level,

00:53:18.210 --> 00:53:20.140
because they have too
many people running.

00:53:20.140 --> 00:53:21.990
And that's a product
of a system that

00:53:21.990 --> 00:53:27.250
just doesn't allow us to say
more than we were able to.

00:53:27.250 --> 00:53:29.370
SPEAKER: Rob and
Krist, thank you.

00:53:29.370 --> 00:53:33.020
[APPLAUSE]

